doc.title: China Property Weekly Wrap
doc.source_uri: 2025-09-02/Week 35 Wrap - Transactions improved modestly but sentiment softened; urban renewal remains policymaker focus_2025-09-02

passages.text: On the policy front, the State Council issued Opinions on Promoting High- Quality Urban Development, which outlined priorities including 1) revitalizing urban property stock by comprehensively surveying existing urban buildings, facilities and land, which will enable the re- purposing of underutilized properties such as outdated factories, vacant buildings, and idle traditional commercial facilities, and improve their operational performance under enhanced property management. Revitalization of underutilized land was also highlighted; 2) advancing development of high- quality housing ("好房子"), supported by initiatives to elevate the quality of property management services, promote the redevelopment of urban villages and dilapidated housing, encourage in- situ renewal and reconstruction of old residential properties, and renovate aging urban communities. These initiatives are echoed at the local level, with both Shanghai and Guangzhou announcing plans to accelerate urban village redevelopment.

In terms of market performance, primary transactions continued to improve, while secondary stayed flattish. That said, sentiment edged lower with modest decline in new home search activity (- 0.8% wow) and secondary visitor traffic (- 2% wow), while secondary new supply rose (+ 7% wow). Zooming in on Shanghai's performance during its 1st week since further HPR relaxation: while its new home sales (web- registration based, lagging auction) asaction by 2- 3 weeks) declined 27% wow, sentiment already showed notable improvement with new home search activity rising 6% wow, while agents' segment (CSI) improved 5pp wow.

New homes sales volume on average was \(+19\%\) wow and \(+1\%\) yoy with tier- 2 and Central Western outperforming, while new home search activities fell \(0.8\%\) wow. Secondary transactions on average were \(+1\%\) wow and \(+6\%\) yoy, with price appreciation expectations improved for agents but stayed flattish for homeowners.

Secondary transactions on average were \(+1\%\) wow and \(+6\%\) yoy, with price appreciation expectations improved for agents but stayed flattish for homeowners.

- August: Primary GFA sold on median was \(-12\%\) mom and was \(-11\%\) yoy, where tier-1/2/3 was \(-29\% / - 3\% / - 13\%\) mom and \(-33\% / - 3\% / - 15\%\) yoy, respectively. Secondary GFA sold on median was \(-7\%\) mom and \(-1\%\) yoy, where tier-1/2/3 was flat/\(-5\% /-10\%\) mom and \(+5\% /+2\% /-1\%\) yoy, respectively.

- YTD: Primary GFA sold was \(-5\%\) yoy on a city-average basis and \(-3\%\) yoy on an aggregated volume basis; secondary GFA sold was \(+12\%\) yoy on a city-average basis and \(+13\%\) yoy on an aggregated volume basis.
- Inventory balance was \(+0.2\%\) wow and \(-3.7\%\) from end-24 level, with inventory months at 25.8 (vs. average 26.0 in July-25).

- Valuation: Offshore coverage developers on average saw share price \(-4\%\) wow (vs. \(-3\%\) for MSCI China), with CRL (1109.HK, Buy, on CL) and COLI (0688.HK, Buy) outperforming at \(-1\%\) wow; Onshore coverage developers averaged \(-4\%\) wow (vs. \(+1\%\) for CSI 300), with CMSK (001979.SZ, Neutral) outperforming at \(-1\%\) wow. Our offshore/onshore coverage now trades at an average \(33\% /10\%\) discount to end-2025E NAV and \(0.6X / 0.5X\) 2025E P/B.
- Completions: GSPC tracker indicates c.20% yoy decline in Aug-25 (vs. \(-29\%\) /teens level yoy decline in July-25 by NBS/GSe and \(-17\%\) yoy in 7M25) and \(-10\%\) yoy in FY25E per GSe.

- New starts: We expect new starts to record mid-teens level yoy decline in Aug (vs. \(-15\%\) /mid-teens level yoy decline in July-25 by NBS/GSe), based on the land sales trends in 300 cities and nationwide cement shipment ratio (-2pp wow to \(44\%\) ).
- Home appliance sales overall are likely to record yoy decline in Aug, based on secondary sales trends in c.20 cities.
- GTV for BEKE (new and existing) likely improved \(4\%\) yoy (-7\%/+9\%\text{for new/existing}) \text{in July-Aug.}\)
